AB  - More than 2000 cases of vaping-associated lung injury have been reported
      in a recent outbreak, including >40 deaths. Although chest imaging is
      integral in the evaluation of these patients and is often abnormal, the
      spectrum of findings and the role of imaging in the diagnosis are not
      widely appreciated. The aim of this review is to highlight the imaging
      findings of vaping-associated lung injury. Basilar-predominant
      ground-glass opacities and/or consolidations, often with areas of
      subpleural or lobular sparing, are the most common pattern, and many other
      patterns are known to occur. Radiologists are encouraged to become
      familiar with the different imaging patterns of vaping-associated lung
      injury. The diagnosis should be considered in patients who have vaped
      within 90 days of onset of symptoms and present with bilateral lung
      opacities.
